        <h2 id="what-is">What is ProWritingAid?</h2>
        <p>ProWritingAid is a grammar, spelling, and style editor built for long-form writers. Where Grammarly optimises for short, fast feedback inside email and chat, ProWritingAid optimises for the writer who is going to sit with a 60,000-word manuscript for the next six months. The product runs <strong>25+ writing reports</strong> against your text and surfaces issues by category rather than as inline squiggles.</p>

        <p>The core suite does five things well:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Realtime grammar &amp; spelling</strong> — standard checks across English variants (US, UK, AU, CA)</li>
          <li><strong>Style reports</strong> — sticky sentences, passive voice, vague words, sentence variety, overused phrases</li>
          <li><strong>Structural reports</strong> — pacing, dialogue tags, repetitions, transitions, readability across paragraphs</li>
          <li><strong>AI Sparks</strong> — sentence rephrasing, counterargument generation, paragraph continuation</li>
          <li><strong>Integrations</strong> — Word, Google Docs, Scrivener, Chrome/Edge/Firefox extensions, desktop apps</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What ProWritingAid is <em>not</em>: a keyword research tool, a SERP analyser, a publishing platform, or a content workflow. It assumes you have a draft. It makes the draft better. Everything before and after — research, brief, distribution — is on you.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>ProWritingAid was founded in 2012 by Chris Banks and is headquartered in London. The company is <strong>bootstrapped and profitable</strong>, with a customer base estimated at 3M+ writers, with a strong concentration in fiction, screenwriting, and academic publishing. That focus is why the editor goes deep on pacing, repetition, and dialogue — features Grammarly has never prioritised.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">ProWritingAid features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is wide. Here is what matters in daily use, organised by what the report set actually does for you.</p>

        <h3>1. The 25+ writing reports</h3>
        <p>This is the headline feature. Where Grammarly gives you a single score and inline suggestions, ProWritingAid gives you a menu of dedicated reports you can run on any document. The most-used ones in our testing:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Style report</strong> — passive voice, hidden verbs, vague modifiers, repeated sentence starts</li>
          <li><strong>Overused words</strong> — flags every "really", "very", "just", "actually" so you can cut them</li>
          <li><strong>Sticky sentences</strong> — sentences with too many glue words that slow the reader down</li>
          <li><strong>Sentence variety</strong> — visualises sentence length to spot monotonous rhythm</li>
          <li><strong>Pacing report</strong> — finds slow passages (high description, low action) that drag the read</li>
          <li><strong>Dialogue report</strong> — checks tag balance, adverb overuse, and dialogue-to-narration ratio</li>
          <li><strong>Repeats report</strong> — flags repeated words and phrases within configurable windows</li>
          <li><strong>Readability</strong> — Flesch, Flesch-Kincaid, and Coleman-Liau scores per paragraph</li>
          <li><strong>Cliches &amp; redundancies</strong> — surfaces phrases readers have seen a thousand times</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If you write fiction, you will use 6–8 of these on every chapter. If you write blog posts, you will use 2–3. The depth is the moat.</p>

        <h3>2. AI Sparks — the assistant layer</h3>
        <p>Added in 2023, AI Sparks bolts a generative layer onto the editor. You select a sentence and ask it to rephrase, shorten, expand, or generate a counterargument. The output is grounded in your surrounding context, which is more useful than a blank-page ChatGPT prompt. Limits apply per plan — Premium gives moderate Sparks credits per month, Premium Pro gives a higher allowance.</p>

        <h3>3. Integrations</h3>
        <p>ProWritingAid plugs into the tools writers already use: Microsoft Word (desktop add-in), Google Docs (sidebar extension), Scrivener (file import/export), Chrome/Edge/Firefox (browser extension), and standalone desktop apps for Windows and macOS. The Scrivener integration is the single feature that converts novelists — most other editors ignore it entirely.</p>

        <h3>4. Style guides &amp; house rules</h3>
        <p>Teams on the higher tier can build custom style guides — disallowed words, preferred spellings, brand terminology — and enforce them across every check. Useful for agencies, publishers, and any team that has fought "is it ecommerce or e-commerce" in pull requests.</p>

        <h3>5. The desktop app</h3>
        <p>Free-standing app for Windows and macOS. Works offline for the core grammar and style checks (Sparks requires internet). Heavy users prefer the desktop over the browser because the editor stays fast at 50,000+ word documents — a length the Google Docs extension struggles with.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">⚠️ What it does not do</div>
